inine form of   Long   ‘long, tall’.","French (<b>Longé</b>): derivative of Old French <i>longe</i> ‘(leather) thong’, used in a transferred sense as a topographic name for someone who lived on a long, narrow stretch of terrain."],"variants":[{"name":"Lange","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans, Erwin, Heinz, Horst, Otto, Wolfgang, Ernst, Helmut, Hermann, Manfred, Reinhold.","German, Scandinavian, and Dutch: variant of   Lang   ‘long’. This surname is also found in Poland and in France (Alsace and Lorraine). Compare   De Lange  .","French: variant, with fused definite article <i>l'</i>, of   Ange   2. Compare   Longe   1."]}]},{"name":"Edith","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old English female personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>gӯð</i> ‘strife’. This was borne by a daughter (  961–984 ) of Edgar the Peaceful. (She was named in accordance with the common Old English practice of repeating name elements within a family.) She spent her short life in a convent, and is regarded as a saint."],"variants":[{"name":"Edyth","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Edith ."]},{"name":"Edythe","meanings":["From an Old English female personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>gӯð</i> ‘strife’. This was borne by a daughter (  961–984 ) of Edgar the Peaceful. (She was named in accordance with the common Old English practice of repeating name elements within a family.) She spent her short life in a convent, and is regarded as a saint."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Edith Longe was born in 1502, in Semington, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir Thomas Longe of Drayton-Cerne, Knight of the Garter and Bath, was 52 and her mother, Lady Margery Darell, was 41. She had at least 2 daughters with John Burley. She died after 1523, in Semington, Wiltshire, England, and was buried in Semington, Wiltshire, England."},"e